Right after, a group of the hostess's friends arrived. She promptly ignored me, left me waiting in the lobby without saying anything, and gave the last patio table to her friends who came in after and we ended up waiting over 30 min for the next table on the patio. Once we were sat, they only had one server working on the patio so we waited well over 20 min before any took our order & they only checked on us once throughout the meal (not the servers fault per say). He then brought the bill without even asking if we wanted anything else (which we did). There are tons of great restaurants in DC, it simply isnt worth spending all the money on this place.

I really wanted to love this place - good ambience, service was decent, and location is convenient to where I live.  However, in my experience in having had good Italian food before, I have to say Lupo Verde is disappointing.  Regardless of the price (DC prices come standard on 14th st) the food needs to be on point when the restaurant holds itself out to be Italian.  The complementary bread was not fresh and seemed warmed because of heat lamps.  The Cesar salad had no flavor because there was plain romaine with no light dressing nor cheese.  The pasta was taken out 1 minute before al dente meaning the pasta was chewy but too chewy to enjoy.  I appreciate the small portion sizes (could be too small for big eaters) but you have to cook the pasta correctly if this is an Italian restaurant.  Spend your money and time at Red Hen, Ghibellina, or Floriana.

One of the better meals I’ve had in a long time. From atmosphere to the product they put out, I would  highly recommend making this a regular stop when dining out. The staff was very knowledgeable when it came to the menu, the specials were described to the utmost perfection. My wife and I chose to eat at the bar versus waiting for a table and we let the bartender basically order for us. We thoroughly enjoyed they witty banter between the bartender and the Italian manager, they seemed to really enjoy themselves while continuing to get the job done and maintain a professional level of service. It was quite entertaining to watch the two of them go back and forth. We were thrilled to add truffle to our pasta and chicken (because who doesn’t love truffle!)  and everything we ate was paired perfectly with wine the that was suggested. The octopus was prepared by far the best way I’ve ever tasted. The music was also a lovely addition to what was an overall perfect date night. We can’t wait to come back with friends!! Thanks for your hospitality and what we will now certainly  add to our regular stops when it comes to family celebrations and dining out!

I researched several nice Italian restaurants for my best friend's farewell dinner before settling on Lupo Verde. Although we were both beyond excited to give it a try, we were appalled by the lack of service. My friend ordered the gnocchi (which we had planned to share with the cacio e pepe), but the server incorrectly put her order in as agnolotti del plin (a meat dish) which was later brought to the table. When my friend politely confronted the server about the mishap, the server offered a short apology and advised my friend not to correct the order because the kitchen was busy. She also told my friend that the agnolotti del plin was far and away better than the gnocchi, and in so much implied that my friend should be grateful for the swap. I too experienced an issue with my order as I received a cavolo nero salad covered with anchovies despite asking the server's assurance that it it was vegetarian. In all, I would be very hesitant to return or recommend Lupo Verde to anyone. No one should pay $80 for an alcohol-less meal for two unless stellar service is involved, which in my experience, it was not. One saving grace is that Ice Cream Jubilee is next door!

Was weary at first, the decor is very modern bar like and the whole restaurant smelled of stale beer.....the dishes are more complex than traditional Italian, but I was very suprised. Started with the prosciutto and melon, not what I was expecting but the prosciutto was very fresh and the dish was tasty. Had the Agnolotti del plin as an entre (Pasta bolognese) the homemade pasta was perfect and the sauce was delicious.  I'm pretty particular when it comes to a Italian cooking and that sauce was spot on.  The canoli for dessert was made properly (unlike many places around here) but cream was a little runny. Overall delicious food, great service, a little pricey, but would definitely recommend.

Anche se hanno cambiato ricette classiche un po’ per clienti piuttosto americani, i piatti sono buoni, carciofi alla giudea da favola, pasta fatto a mano in casa, e un ampio scelto di vino (sempre con prezzi astronomici, come si deve in America, tipo $45 per una bottiglia). Comunque, ottima scelta per chi manca il bel paese.
Nice cozy setting for some craft cocktails
Bad pizza
Always a solid pick...3-5 stars depending on the night but gives me my fix of authentic Italian when I am in the mood!

Went to this restaurant while touring colleges last week on the most beautiful spring day.  Being tourists, didn't think we would need a reservation.  Bad mistake, however, one of the managers, Michael, was so kind, he was able to find a table for us and outside no less.  What a nice surprise and the level of hospitality and service was truly commendable.  Food was amazingly delicious, from their salads, artichoke and burrata appetizers, and the homemade pastas...wow to die for.  Thank you Michael for a great dinner experience!

We went here for brunch.  The coffee was good but the meal was just ok. The service was slow. My fried egg really runny and the greens were a bit soggy from a dressing added that wasn't mentioned in the menu. I don't know why restaurants feel the need to put mystery dressing on nice greens.  The water is served room temp.  Tip: ask for your dressing on the side even for items with no supposed dressing.

Food was amazing! I don't think I've ever had Italian food that tasted so good (and I'm half Italian so shhhh). And the staff were fantastic. My friend and I went on a busy night without a reservation and they accommodated us and made us feel like welcomed guests. I am now obsessed with the place and can't wait to go back.
Okay but not very impressive for the price.

We had a fun and delicious dining experience here last night. Rico made the evening for us! He paired my meal with a delicous wine and had wonderful recommendations for our entrees. Highly recommend dining here, hope to re-visit  before we leave DC as we are in town for a wedding
Great food.
Best Italian food in town for the money.  One of the few places on 14th where the food is consistently exceptional.
Food delicious. Wine pairinh on point. Waitress: Ann Marie, is the best! Great attitude and has a likeable personality. Knows the food there and pushes good choices not pricy ones

Came in for a late brunch. Food was ok, good even but the service was sub par especially considering the overpriced food. Our server kept dripping water all over the table and the food every time he refilled out glasses. Won't be going back in a hurry.
Delicious food
Pretty mediocre food that's overpriced. Manager was incredibly rude and insulting.
Nice Italian spot.  A bit pricey for the food but enjoyed it.  Fantastic service.
Good atmosphere. Friendly bartender.
One of the best restaurants in DC, and charming with a vibe. Staff are always warm and professional. Foods always delicious

Great food and a fun vibe, but kinda meh for brunch, so four instead of five stars.  Quality of the food was great for my wife's cacio e pepe, but my meal was touted as having this medley of delicious things with my eggs, yet the dish just seemed like the eggs with a mere garnish of a toast point and a single, paltry sliver of speck. Underwhelming and insubstantial, especially given the price. Even if they were two freshest of farm eggs and other ingredients, the whole dish's contents would total no more than $5, meaning it was marked up nearly 200%. I'm all for a good restaurant getting paid, but I want my money's worth.  Dinner is a different story. Great meals to be had and of normal portion proportions. Service was arguably better in the evening, as well, but it was not memorable in either case, which I view as a good thing, as they were efficient and not a distraction from my company. The brunch service was a little more inattentive.  In sum, it's a typical DC restaurant. High quality food, high prices, solid service for the most part, and hit or miss on whether you'll love it or hate it, depending on your own experience and appetite. For me the quality of the food bumps it up a bit above average. YMMV.

Lupo Verde is an excellent establishment! There is a gorgeous ecstatic, wonderful service, and amazing food. The Acialatielli al Nero was out of this world! Everybody must visit this fine Italian restaurant!
My pasta had a very mediocre sauce. Wine list not to my liking. Awkward layout. Cozy though. Friendly wait staff .

This place was disappointing. Sure the atmosphere was nice, and so were the people. But I came to this restaurant starving and I got a plate of spaghetti (no chicken or meatballs) for $18. The portion was so freaking small. I left hungry.
Amazing cheese and fresh made pasta!
The foie gras is incredibly delicious.
Quaint italian place.  Really enjoyed food and service
The food is simply amazing. Brunch is great, all dishes are full of flavor and the service is great.

So good. So good. So good! The wait for our table was a bit ridiculous (we were told 15 minutes and over an hour later we were sat). But the food is fantastic! The atmosphere is fun. The cute little outdoor table made it all worth the wait.
The food and service is excellent every time.

I can't stress enough how great this place is! If you're feeling adventurous, don't look at the menu. Instead, strike up a conversation with your server. Start by sharing what you like in a wine and the rest will fall into place. I've done this several times and not once have I been disappointed by the meal they chose for me based on my first glass of wine. This is by far my favorite restaurant and it'll be yours too.
Great food
Fantastic food and atmosphere. I brought my girlfriend here to celebrate her birthday and everything was perfect. Highly recommend!
Great restaurant!!! Our food was absolutely delicious and very fresh. The mozzarella was incredible and the entrees were both amazing!
Lovely atmosphere, staff and food. Would happily return.
Plates are too small for the price.  Very loud so difficult to have a conversation.  Professional and young crowd.

Lupo Verde is located towards the end of the popular 14th st corridor but features delicious pizzas, cheeses, charcuterie, and other small plates.  While on the pricer side -- I found their menu to be all around excellent.  Note that during "tween" hours (i think 3-5) they only serve pizzas, salads, and meat/cheese dishes. Which isnt honestly an issue -- but if you want the full menu, be sure to be there during core hours
Unique food and atmosphere.
Truly remarkable food, great atmosphere, and pretty reasonable prices. I'm going back for sure. (Get the fried artichoke app!)
Great crafty cocktails!

Delicious restaurant. We wanted to eat there for dinner but went for a brunch instead. No deception at all. The food was incredibly tasty. Looking good, you could feel all the ingredients. The terrasse is so cute and the service was very nice. Want to come back there
A little pricey but well worth it for the food quality.

Even though in my business I seek the feedback I'm not the greatest at leaving reviews! As a matter of fact this may actually be my first! This place and the team make it more than a meal. Mattheo (Exec Chef) personally came out to make recommendations while he was passing by, our servers felt like friends and the food - on point!  Highly recommend a stop if your going by 14th St.
The portions aren't large but the food is quite tasty. The scallops are amazing.
Good service. I like the interior. We came here for lunch on a Sunday afternoon. Seafood pasta was too fishy for my taste. Cacio e pepe for the win!

Authentic Italian. This isn't a regular huge-plate-of-noodles American-Italian spot. Still filling portions, but not over the top. Focus is on the quality of the ingredients and interesting menu choices. Not the cheapest but fair for the food quality and excellent service.  Summer veggies were VERY fresh and full-flavored, and I appreciated the restraint of letting many of the ingredients speak for themselves without too much sauce. (I.e. the fresh burrata and tomatoes, fried artichokes, candied tomato salad...)  Menu has also changed between my several visits; some core dishes stayed the same but a lot of appetizers rotated, which was fun.  Wine was spectacular (we just asked waiter for recommendations; was a good Italian wine and didn't break the bank).  The second floor dining room also has some large tables making it easy for groups.
